    <article class="prose" style="margin-top:1rem">
      <p>A river without banks is a lake. It’s beautiful, but it doesn’t go anywhere.</p>
      <p>Our projects gave us banks — not to confine us, but to lend direction and pressure, the two forces that turn still water into a current. These banks are living structures; they erode and rebuild as we move. The proof that they work is simple: the water keeps singing.</p>
      <p>When we choose constraints with care, we don’t shrink the self — we sharpen it. Each boundary is a promise to flow, to carry silt from one reach of the mind into another, to meet the sea having gathered what we would otherwise leave scattered on the shore.</p>
